    <h1>Michigan Restaurant Insurance</h1>
    <p class="lead">Restaurants carry risks most businesses never face — liquor liability, fire and equipment breakdown, food spoilage, slip-and-falls, and employee turnover. We build the right package across multiple carriers so one bad night doesn't put your kitchen out of business.</p>

    <div class="trust-band">
      <span class="trust-band-item"><span class="stars">★★★★★</span> 4.9 on Google</span>
      <span class="trust-band-item">Best of the Best &mdash; 8 years running <span class="sub">(2018&ndash;2025)</span></span>
      <span class="trust-band-item">20+ commercial carriers</span>
      <span class="trust-band-item">Family-owned since 1981</span>
    </div>

    <h2>What we do for restaurant clients</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Right-sized packages</strong> — we bundle general liability, property, and business income into a restaurant BOP where it fits, and add the specialty coverages your concept actually needs.</li>
      <li><strong>Liquor liability done right</strong> — if you serve alcohol, Michigan's dram shop law puts you on the hook. We make sure your liquor liability limits and forms match your exposure and your license.</li>
      <li><strong>Multi-carrier shopping</strong> — we shop your restaurant across multiple carriers to find the best combination of price and protection, not a single take-it-or-leave-it quote.</li>
      <li><strong>Coverage for the gaps</strong> — equipment breakdown, food spoilage, assault &amp; battery, and employee dishonesty are commonly missed. We make sure they're considered.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Restaurants we write</h2>
    <p>Full-service restaurants, fast-casual and quick-service, cafes and coffee shops, food trucks and mobile vendors, bars and taverns, breweries, bakeries, and catering operations.</p>

    <h2>Coverages restaurants usually need</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>General liability</strong> — slip-and-falls and other third-party injury or property damage claims.</li>
      <li><strong>Liquor liability</strong> — protection under Michigan's dram shop law if you serve alcohol.</li>
      <li><strong>Commercial property &amp; business income</strong> — your building, kitchen, furnishings, and lost income while you recover from a covered loss.</li>
      <li><strong>Equipment breakdown</strong> — a failed walk-in cooler, oven, or HVAC system.</li>
      <li><strong>Food spoilage / contamination</strong> — lost inventory from a refrigeration failure or power outage.</li>
      <li><strong>Workers compensation</strong> — required for nearly every Michigan employer (see our <a href="../workers-compensation/">workers comp page</a>).</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Common questions</h2>
    <details class="faq-item"><summary>What insurance does a Michigan restaurant need?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Most Michigan restaurants need a core package of general liability, commercial property, and business income, plus liquor liability if you serve alcohol, equipment breakdown, food spoilage/contamination coverage, and workers compensation for employees. A Business Owners Policy (BOP) bundles several of these; specialty exposures like assault and battery or food trucks are added on. We build the program around your concept.</p></div></details>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>Do I need liquor liability insurance in Michigan?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>If you serve or sell alcohol, yes. Under Michigan's dram shop law, a restaurant or bar can be held liable for damages caused by a visibly intoxicated or underage patron it served. General liability usually excludes alcohol-related claims, so liquor liability is a separate, essential coverage. Many landlords and the state liquor license process also require proof of it.</p></div></details>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>How much does restaurant insurance cost in Michigan?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Cost depends on your sales, square footage, whether you serve alcohol, your kitchen equipment, payroll, and claims history. A small cafe pays far less than a full-service restaurant with a bar. Because we're independent, we shop your restaurant across multiple carriers to find the best combination of price and coverage rather than a single quote.</p></div></details>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>Does restaurant insurance cover food spoilage and equipment breakdown?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>It can, when those coverages are included. Equipment breakdown covers a failed walk-in cooler, oven, or HVAC unit, and food spoilage/contamination coverage pays for lost inventory and, in some forms, lost income when refrigeration fails or a power outage spoils stock. These are commonly overlooked add-ons we make sure are on your policy.</p></div></details>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>Do you insure food trucks, bars, and breweries?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Yes. We write the full range of Michigan food-and-beverage businesses: full-service and fast-casual restaurants, cafes, food trucks and mobile vendors, bars and taverns, breweries, and bakeries. Each has different forms and markets, and we have carriers for each.</p></div></details>

